While some believe that the name of "Hatsunia" refers to the story that the Hatsunese language was the first to be spoken in the world, in reality it refers to Hatsunia's geographical position, putting it on the east of, say, China, which makes it so the first sounds of the day are heard in Hatsunia before they are in Asia.

by Shtet » Tue Apr 28, 2020 1:29 pm

The endonym of Hatsunia is "Hatsune-koku" which translates to 'land of the first sounds.' This refers to the far-eastern position of the country similarly to Japan's nickname of 'land of the rising sun.' Further, the name "Hatsune" by itself is never used to refer to the country in Hatsunese, but is often used in its adjective form.
